"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old man returns to his General Practice clinic after the Christmas period with a 6kg weight gain over the past two months. During the last few weeks he has been feeling more short of breath on exertion, and struggles to walk to the shops despite doing this regularly prior to Christmas. His medical history includes ischaemic heart disease, poorly controlled hypertension and type 2 diabetes. His diabetes was diagnosed six years ago and he has struggled to control his blood sugars despite attempted lifestyle interventions and medical management over this time. His medications include amlodipine, ramipril, metformin, gliclazide and aspirin. He is an active smoker with a 40-pack-year history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he appears a little breathless, but otherwise well. His pulse rate is 92/min and blood pressure 166/95mmHg. Cardiorespiratory exam reveals a laterally displaced apex beat, fine crepitations at both lung bases, and pitting oedema to the mid-shins bilaterally. His routine HBA1c indicates worsening glycaemic control. You consider starting him on either insulin or pioglitazone to improve his diabetic control. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors would best support the decision to prescribe insulin rather than pioglitazone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["History of ischaemic heart disease","Failure of lifestyle modifications","Failure of dual-agent therapy","Examination findings","Sulfonylurea use"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s \u003Cstrong\u003Eexamination findings \u003C/strong\u003Ein conjunction with his recent weight gain and exertional dyspnoea are highly suggestive of fluid overload and congestive cardiac failure. Pioglitazone is contraindicated in heart failure due to its fluid retentive effects, meaning insulin would be the preferred option in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehistory of ischaemic heart disease\u003C/strong\u003E is not a contraindication to pioglitazone, which also modulates lipid metabolism and decreases risk of atherosclerotic events.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFailure of lifestyle modifications \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Efailure of dual-agent therapy\u003C/strong\u003E do not inherently support the choice of either diabetic agent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESulfonylurea use \u003C/strong\u003Eis not an indication to choose insulin over pioglitazone - given their similar mechanisms of action and the risk for hypoglycaemia in both agents, patients are typically managed with either insulin \u003Cstrong\u003Eor\u003C/strong\u003E a sulfonylurea, rather than both.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thiazolidinediones (\u0022glitazones\u0022) are contraindicated in cardiac failure due to their potential to cause fluid retention."],"references":["Derosa G. Efficacy and tolerability of pioglitazone in patients with type 2 diabetes mellitus: comparison with other oral antihyperglycaemic agents. Drugs. 2010 Oct 22;70(15):1945-61. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20883052/","Australian Type 2 Diabetes Glycaemic Management Algorithm [Internet]. RACGP. National Diabetes Services Scheme; 2024 [cited 2025 Apr 14]. Available from: racgp.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80949"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1400"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80949"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-14T17:22:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-14T17:23:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1400"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98544"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":